    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="loc.03629.003_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place">
                        <handShift rend="printed"/> LAW OFFICE OF</name>
                    <name type="place">CHARLES H. ROBERTS,</name>
                    <name type="place">GENERAL LAW.</name>
                    <name type="place">PATENT LAW.</name>
                    <name type="place">ROOM 20.</name>
                    <name type="place">NO. 180 SOUTH CLARK STREET.</name>
                    <name type="place">Chicago,<ptr target="loc.03629_n5"/></name>
                        <handShift rend="manuscript"/><date when="1891-11-25">Nov. 25 <handShift rend="printed"/>189<handShift rend="manuscript"/>1</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Mr Walt Whitman</salute>
                <salute>Camden,</salute>
                <salute>N.J.</salute>
                <salute>Dear Sir:</salute>    
            </opener> 
            <p>Years ago, centennial year,<ptr target="n0435"/> I spoke with you on Camden Ferry<ptr target="loc.03629_n4"/> about sunset, Celia Thaxter,<ptr target="loc.03629_n3"/>
                the man o war bird,<ptr target="n0639"/> John Burroughs,<ptr target="n0129"/> etc I
                was then, or had been, mechanic and with Star &amp; Sons, although a
                western-man.</p> 
            <p>Now, at Chicago, I have just bought "Good-Bye My Fancy,"<ptr target="loc.07894_n2"/> and renew the acquaintance.</p>
            <p>I shall send you, tomorrow, a little book of mine, which some people read; and which
                I think myself has green in it, though it may not be worth the browsing. I doubt if
                I send it to be read, or even looked at, but rather—as a tribute to courage,
                it is all I have. Look at its bill of fare; and—hand it to someone else,
                or—heave it away.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute>Yours very sincerely</salute>
                <signed>Charles H Roberts.</signed>
            </closer>
            <note type="editorial" place="left" resp="#ht">see notes Dec 4 1891</note>
